<!--
structure of atoms
--->

<p class="definition" data-word = 'atomic number'>
    The number of protons in the nucleus of an atom.
    All nuclei of a particular element have
    <emph>the same</emph>
    number of protons.
</p>
<p class="definition" data-word = 'Mass Number'>
    THe number of protons + the number of neutrons.
    All nuclei DO NOT have the same number of neutrons,
    and DO NOT have the same mass number
</p>
<p class="definition" data-word = 'isotope'>
    All atoms of one element have the <emph>same number</emph>
    of protons, but they do not have the same mass number.
    Different <emph>isotopes</emph> of one element are different
    atoms of the same element with different mass numbers.
</p>

<p class="definition" data-word = 'Important fact on isotopes'>
    When you are in chemistry class, and learning about the different
    chemical reactions that an atom undergoes.
    In this case, the isotopes of an atom don't matter very much.
    However, when dealing with nuclear reactions,
    the isotopes you have is one of the most important factors.
</p>

